{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Rows with missing required fields are rejected and appear in the dead-letter queue with the original row number.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A unit test on the validator alone can miss failures in CSV row-number tracking and DLQ wiring. The failure boundary is the interaction between CSV parsing, schema validation, and DLQ persistence.","test_description":"Run the ingest pipeline against a small CSV fixture with known missing required fields and mixed valid rows, using real parser + validator + DLQ sink (e.g., local queue/table). Assert invalid rows are emitted to DLQ with exact original CSV row numbers and valid rows continue downstream.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The transformation correctly converts date strings in multiple formats (ISO 8601, US, European) to a single canonical format.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is primarily deterministic transformation logic at a single function/object boundary. Real failures are usually parsing/normalization edge cases, which a focused unit test can catch without I/O.","test_description":"Test the date-normalization function directly with a table of ISO 8601, US, and European inputs (including ambiguous and invalid cases) and assert canonical output format and expected failures.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A CSV file with 500,000 rows completes processing within the configured timeout without running out of memory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Timeout and memory behavior depend on runtime, process memory limits, streaming behavior, and end-to-end I/O throughput. In-process mocks can hide backpressure and buffering issues.","test_description":"Execute the pipeline as a real process with a 500k-row fixture, real storage/database endpoints used in staging-like conditions, and configured timeout/memory limits. Assert completion before timeout, peak memory below threshold, and no OOM/kill signals.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the S3 bucket returns a transient 503 error, the pipeline retries with exponential backoff rather than failing the entire batch.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Retry correctness can be hidden by SDK/client mocks; real HTTP status handling, retry middleware, and timing behavior are the failure boundary. This needs real network behavior (even to a local test server).","test_description":"Run pipeline against an HTTP/S3-compatible test endpoint that returns 503 for initial requests then success. Measure attempted request timestamps and assert exponential backoff pattern, bounded retry count, and eventual batch success.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Rows successfully written to PostgreSQL are not duplicated if the pipeline is restarted mid-batch.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This behavior depends on process restart semantics plus durable DB state and idempotency/checkpoint logic. Mocking restart or DB writes can miss real duplicate-write failures.","test_description":"Start a real pipeline process writing to a real PostgreSQL instance, force termination mid-batch after a known subset commits, restart processing, and assert final table contains exactly one copy per logical row (via unique key/count checks).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
